.TH "SANITIZER.REMOVEELEMENT" "3JS" "January 16, 2026" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Sanitizer.removeElement \- Sanitizer: removeElement() method
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]removeElement()\f[B]\f[R] method of the
\f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] interface sets the specified element be removed
from the output when the sanitizer is used.
.PP
The method can be used with either an allow configuration or a remove
configuration.
If used with a remove configuration, the specified element is added to
the \f[CR]removeElements\f[R] array.
If used with an allow configuration, the element is removed from the
\f[CR]elements\f[R] array (if present).
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
removeElement(element)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]element\f[R]
A string indicating the name of the element to be disallowed, or an
object with the following properties:
.RS
.TP
\f[B]name\f[R]
A string containing the name of the element.
.TP
\f[B]namespace\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A string containing the namespace of the element.
The default namespace is
\f[CR]\(dqhttp://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\(dq\f[R].
.RE
.SS Return value
\f[CR]true\f[R] if the operation changed the configuration to disallow
the element, and \f[CR]false\f[R] if the element was already disallowed.
.PP
Note that \f[CR]false\f[R] might be returned if the internal
configuration:
.IP \(bu 2
defines an \f[CR]elements\f[R] array and the element is already omitted
(it does not need to be removed)
.IP \(bu 2
instead defines the \f[CR]removeElements\f[R] array and the specified
element is already present (and is hence already filtered)
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS How to disallow elements
This example shows how \f[CR]removeElement()\f[R] is used to specify an
element to be \(lqdisallowed\(rq.
.SS JavaScript
The code first creates a new \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] object that initially
allows \f[CR]<div>\f[R] and \f[CR]<script>\f[R] elements, and that
replaces \f[CR]<span>\f[R] elements with their child elements.
.PP
The code then calls \f[CR]removeElement()\f[R] to add \f[CR]<p>\f[R],
\f[CR]<script>\f[R] and \f[CR]<span>\f[R] elements to the
\f[CR]removeElements\f[R] list in the configuration.
Note that adding \f[CR]<script>\f[R] and \f[CR]<span>\f[R] removes the
elements from their original lists.
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// Create sanitizer using SanitizerConfig\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] sanitizer = \f[B]new\f[R] Sanitizer({
  elements: [\(dqdiv\(dq, \(dqscript\(dq],
  replaceWithChildrenElements: [\(dqspan\(dq],
});

\f[I]// Disallow the <p> element\f[R]
sanitizer.removeElement(\(dqp\(dq);

\f[I]// Disallow the <script> element\f[R]
sanitizer.removeElement(\(dqscript\(dq);
\f[I]// Disallow the <span> element\f[R]
sanitizer.removeElement(\(dqspan\(dq);

\f[I]// Log the sanitizer configuration\f[R]
\f[B]let\f[R] sanitizerConfig = sanitizer.get();
log(JSON.stringify(sanitizerConfig, \f[B]null\f[R], 2));
.EE
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] This configuration is provided for demonstration only.
Sanitizer configurations should include either just the allowed elements
(\f[CR]elements\f[R]) or just the disallowed elements
(\f[CR]removeElements\f[R]), but not both.
In this case only the \f[CR]<div>\f[R] element is allowed and all other
elements will be removed from the input: so the removed elements have no
effect.
.RE
.SS Results
The final configuration is logged below.
